column10: 1.2: Does the format have a published open specification?
column11: 1.3: If there is a published specification, has it been approved and published by an internationally recognized standards organization?
column12: 1.4: When was the format specification for this version last updated (or, if the last updated date is not available, when was it created)?
column14: 2.1: Has the file format commonly been used to create or maintain permanent records within the federal government at any point in time?
column15: 2.2: Is the format, or format family, actively maintained and updated by an organization or community?
column16: 2.3: Have the archives or library communities identified the format as one to avoid for creation and transfer of permanent materials?
column18: 3.1: Is the format character-based, rather than binary?
column19: 3.2: Is there an internal signature in an authoritative format registry that can be used to identify a file in this format?
column20: 3.3: Does the format require the use of compression?
column21: 3.4: If the format requires the use of compression, can it be lossy?
column22: 3.5: Does this format support declared or hidden embedded data?
column23: 3.6: If the format supports declared or hidden embedded data, does the format list or provide standard information about embedded data?
column25: 4.1: Does the format natively include metadata that documents the file and the technical environment used to create (and/or modify) it?
column26: 4.2: Does the format support adding embedded descriptive and administrative metadata through manual or automated processes?
column28: 5.1: Does the format require a specific hardware environment, such as a specific graphics card, chipset, or memory requirements, to process or interact with it?
column29: 5.2: Does the format require specific playback hardware (e.g., Blu-Ray, Audio CD, etc) to transfer the format to the NARA environment?
column32: 6.2: If renderers are available, is at least one of them open source?
column33: 6.3: Does the format rely on plug-ins and/or scripts, etc. to render or execute files?
column34: 6.4: Can the format be rendered or executed in more than one computing operating system?
column35: 6.5: Is there software supported by current computing environments that can create the format?
column37: 7.1: Is the format subject to patent claims that may impede the development of open source tools for opening and managing the files?
column38: 7.2: Does the format have open source license terms?
column40: 8.1: Does the format require the use of encryption?
column41: 8.2: If the format requires the use of encryption, is it robust (cryptographically secure)?
column42: 8.3: Does the format natively allow the use of technical protection measures (e.g. digital rights management)?
